{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17536140","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17536140"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:04:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:04:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15596"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15596","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15596"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.39,0.47,0.03,0.09,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8287"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62002"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8287","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8287"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15596"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47448"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1147"},{"type":"tags","id":"2349"},{"type":"tags","id":"2925"},{"type":"tags","id":"2967"},{"type":"tags","id":"4043"},{"type":"tags","id":"4687"},{"type":"tags","id":"4689"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20007"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43588"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62002","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62002"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 79-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of urinary urgency, frequency and occasional urge incontinence. He reports having to rush to the toilet up to six times during the day and three times at night to urinate. He has experienced several episodes of incontinence before reaching the toilet. His medical history includes type 2 diabetes, chronic kidney disease, osteoarthritis of both knees, and a previous transient ischaemic attack. His medications include metformin and paracetamol. He lives independently and walks with a stick.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Digital rectal examination reveals a smooth, non-tender prostate of normal size. Neurological examination of the lower limbs is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urodynamic studies","Post-void residual volume measurement","24-hour pad test","Prostate specific antigen measurement","Computed tomography of the pelvis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms suggestive of overactive bladder syndrome, characterised by urinary urgency, frequency, nocturia, and urge incontinence. Before initiating specific treatment, it is essential to exclude underlying causes, particularly in older adults.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPost-void residual volume measurement\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial investigation. It is non-invasive, easily performed using bladder ultrasound, and helps exclude significant urinary retention which may be contributing to the symptoms. This is particularly important in older men where bladder outlet obstruction may be present despite a normal-feeling prostate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProstate specific antigen measurement\u003C/strong\u003E would not help diagnose or guide initial management of urge incontinence. While it may be appropriate as part of prostate cancer screening, it is not the priority in investigating these symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrodynamic studies\u003C/strong\u003E are specialised tests that may be helpful in complex cases or before surgical intervention, but they are not first-line investigations. They are invasive and should be reserved for cases where initial management has failed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography of the pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E would be excessive as an initial investigation. It may be indicated if there are concerning features such as haematuria or suspected malignancy, which are not present here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E24-hour pad test\u003C/strong\u003E can quantify urine loss but does not help identify the underlying cause of the symptoms. It may be useful in monitoring treatment response but is not the most appropriate initial investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther important initial investigations would include urinalysis to exclude infection, and blood tests to assess renal function and glucose control given his diabetes. After excluding retention and infection, management options would include lifestyle modifications, bladder training, and antimuscarinic medications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Post-void residual measurement is the first-line investigation for urinary symptoms in older adults to exclude urinary retention.","Urge incontinence in older adults requires exclusion of underlying causes including infection, retention, and neurological conditions before specific therapy.","Normal prostate examination does not exclude bladder outlet obstruction in men with lower urinary tract symptoms."],"references":["Hutchinson A, Nesbitt A, Joshi A, Clubb A, Perera M. Overactive bladder syndrome: management and treatment options. Australian journal of general practice. 2020 Sep;49(9):593-8. Available online at ; https://web.archive.org/web/20201105131844id_/https://www1.racgp.org.au/getattachment/6fa7944c-6efd-4768-8a96-b87986e6b651/Overactive-bladder-syndrome.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47448"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15596"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47448"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-16T22:52:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-16T22:53:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8287"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62002"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups